Former President Goodluck Jonathan has been appointed to lead a team of international observers to Sierra Leone’s general elections scheduled to take place on March 7, 2018.
Ikechukwu Eze, the former President’s Media Aide, in a statement, indicated that Jonathan is scheduled to leave for Freetown on Friday as leader of the Election Observation Mission of the Electoral Institute for Sustainable Democracy in Africa (EISA).
Eze observed that Jonathan would be leading the Mission which has observers drawn from civil society organisations and election management bodies from across the continent.
“The former President is pleased to be part of the process in support of a peaceful and transparent election in Sierra Leone,” he remarked.
EISA is a not-for-profit election-focused organization that is working with national, regional, Pan-African and global partners throughout the African continent and is based in South Africa with field offices across the continent and has supported or observed over 100 electoral and political processes in Africa.
EISA has current and past field offices in countries like Burundi, Central African Republic (CAR), Chad, Côte d’Ivoire, Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Gabon, Kenya, Madagascar, Mozambique, Rwanda, Somalia, Sudan, Zambia and Zimbabwe.

